<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-488-202  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 488 202.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  May 28 1990 v12 n22 pS57(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>More choices, more confusion. (fonts for Microsoft Windows 3.0graphical interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gruman, Galen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sophisticated computer fonts have become so popular thattypewritten letters or memos now look unprofessional, and a widevariety of resident printer fonts, font cartridges, anddownloadable soft fonts are available.andP;  Bit-mapped fonts aregenerally used on LaserJets and other limited printers whilehigh-quality PostScript printers and typesetters use outlinefonts.andP;  The new True Type font technology developed jointly by IBMand Microsoft lets users render outline fonts for both the screenand printer in any size on the fly.andP;  HP's new LaserJet III is thefirst truly affordable printer to support outline font technology.andO;Windows 3.0 uses the same font-loading interface as previousWindows versions.andP;  Each printer/port combination can have adifferent font list.andP;  Fonts use special 'width table' metricsfiles, but only the PostScript versions of these can be edited.andO;The upcoming True Type promises faster printing across a varietyof output devices, but Microsoft is unsure how to position it inWindows.andP;  True Type may be incorporated in a future Windowsversion or may be implemented as a dynamic linked library used byapplications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (products).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Product:   Microsoft Windows (Graphical user interface) (design andconstruction).andO;Topic:     FontsWord ProcessingDesktop PublishingGraphical User InterfaceNew Product.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>